Preliminaries

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(tidyverse))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(NHANES))

Task 1: Data Source

I will use the NHANES data set for this project data(NHANES).

This is survey data collected by the US National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) which has conducted a series of health and nutrition surveys since the early 1960s. Since 1999 approximately 5,000 individuals of all ages are interviewed in their homes every year and complete the health examination component of the survey. The health examination is conducted in a mobile examination center (MEC).

Task 2: Load and Tidy the Data

data(NHANES)

columnsToKeep <- c('ID' , 'AgeDecade', 'Diabetes' , 'Gender', 'Race3'
                   , 'RegularMarij', 'SleepTrouble' , 'SurveyYr'
                   , 'HealthGen','Age', 'BMI', 'BPSysAve', 'BPDiaAve', 'DirectChol'
                   , 'Pulse', 'TotChol', 'SleepHrsNight', 'Weight')


# I have selected some columns from the data set and created
# a selected.table


# TIDYING

selected.table <- NHANES[,columnsToKeep]

# selected only Survey year 2011_12 so we can use Race3
selected.table <-  selected.table %>% dplyr::filter(SurveyYr == '2011_12')

# Going to look at those patients who are self-reported health as 'Good'
selected.table <-  selected.table %>% dplyr::filter(HealthGen == 'Good')

# keep complete cases
selected.table <- na.omit(selected.table)

write.csv(x = selected.table, file = 'selectedNHANES.csv')

I selected the following columns:

ID, AgeDecade, Diabetes, Gender, Race3, RegularMarij, SleepTrouble, SurveyYr, HealthGen, Age, BMI, BPSysAve, BPDiaAve, DirectChol, Pulse, TotChol, SleepHrsNight, Weight

I am including only year 2011_12, and those patients who are reporting that they are in good health.

I am keeping only the complete cases.

Task 4: Code Book

Code book of the selected date from NHANES data set.

Variable Type Details
ID character Participant identifier (913 from min 62172 to max 71911)
AgeDecade factor Age category, as decade.
Diabetes factor Yes or No. Reported diabetes or not.
Gender factor Male or Female
Race1 factor Reported race of study participant. Mexican, Hispanic, White, Black, or Other.
RegularMarij factor Yes or No. Uses marujana regularly
SleepTrouble factor Yes or No. Trouble sleeping
SurveyYr numeric Survey years 2009_10 or 2011_12.
HealthGen factor Self reported by Patient. One of Excellent, Very Good, Good, Fair, or Poor.
Age numeric Age in years, age 80 or over recorded as 80.
Height numeric height in cm
BMI numeric Body mass index (weight/height2 in kg/m2).
BPSysAve numeric Combined systolic blood pressure reading
BPDiaAve numeric Combined diastolic blood pressure reading
DirectChol numeric Direct HDL cholesterol in mmol/L.
Pulse numeric 60 second pulse rate
TotChol numeric Total HDL cholesterol in mmol/L.
SleepHrsNight numeric Number of hours of sleep per night.
Weight numeric Weight in kg.

Task 5: My Subjects

The data I have selected from the NHANES contains 913 rows of data from NHANES. NHANES can be treated, for educational purposes, as if it were a simple random sample from the American population. Ref: NHANES documentation obtained from ? NHANES, and website (NHANES WEBSITE)[https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nhanes/index.htm]

All subjects have self-reported health of good, and are part of the 2011_20112 survey, and are complete cases.

Task 6: My Variables

Detailed description

Variable Details
ID Participant identifier (913 participants from ids min 62172 to max 71911)
AgeDecade Age category, as decade. Categorical variable derived from age with levels 0-9, 10-19, 70+
Diabetes Study participant told by a doctor or health professional that they have diabetes. Reported for participants aged 1 year or older as Yes or No.
Gender Male or Female.
Race3 Reported race of study participant, including non-Hispanic Asian category: Mexican, Hispanic, White, Black, Asian, or Other. Not available for 2009-10.
RegularMarij Participant has been/is a regular marijuana user (used at least once a month for a year). Reported for participants aged 18 to 59 years as Yes or No.
SleepTrouble Participant has told a doctor or other health professional that they had trouble sleeping. Reported for participants aged 16 years and older. Coded as Yes or No.
SurveyYr Survey years 2009_10 or 2011_12.
HealthGen Self-reported rating of participants health in general Reported for participants aged 12 years or older. One of Excellent, Verry Good, Good, Fair, or Poor.
Age Age in years, age 80 or over recorded as 80.
BMI Body mass index (weight/height2 in kg/m2). Reported for participants aged 2 years or older.
BPSysAve Combined systolic blood pressure reading, following the procedure outlined for BPXSAR.
BPDiaAve Combined diastolic blood pressure reading, following the procedure outlined for BPXDAR
DirectChol Direct HDL cholesterol in mmol/L. Reported for participants aged 6 years or older.
Pulse 60 second pulse rate
TotChol Total HDL cholesterol in mmol/L. Reported for participants aged 6 years or older.
SleepHrsNight Self-reported number of hours study participant usually gets at night on weekdays or workdays. Reported for participants aged 16 years and older.
Weight Weight in kg.

Task 7: My Planned Linear Regression Model

So the continuous outcome will be BMI, and I am going to look for which factors from those that I have selected that have to do with weight blood pressure, cholesterol, how well they sleep, and for fun if Marijuana use affects diabetes (I have never heard if Marijuana has an effect), and of course if it differs between race. I will test for both Age and AgeDecade, but will only use 1 of the two if it gets used in the model

BMI ~ Weight + BPSysAve + BPDiaAve + (Age or AgeDecade) Pulse + DirectChol + TotChol + SleepHrsNight + RegularMarij + Race3 + Diabetes

Task 8: My Planned Logistic Regression Model

So the binary outcome will be SleepTrouble, and I am going to look for which factors from those that I have selected that have to do with weight blood pressure, cholesterol, how well they sleep, and for fun if Marijuana use affects diabetes (I have no idea about this), and of course if it differs between race. I will test for both Age and AgeDecade, but will only use 1 of the two if it gets used in the model.

SleepTrouble ~ Weight + BPSysAve + BPDiaAve + (Age or AgeDecade) Pulse + DirectChol + TotChol + SleepHrsNight + RegularMarij + Race3 + Diabetes

Task 10: Analysis - Linear regression

model.lm.01 <- lm(formula = BMI ~ Weight + BPSysAve + BPDiaAve + 
                           Age + AgeDecade + Pulse + DirectChol + 
                           TotChol + SleepHrsNight + RegularMarij + 
                           Race3 + Diabetes, data = selected.table)

Task 11: Analysis -Logistic Regression

model.glmLO.01 <- glm(formula = SleepTrouble ~  Weight + BPSysAve + BPDiaAve + Age + 
        AgeDecade +  Pulse + DirectChol + TotChol + SleepHrsNight +
        RegularMarij + Race3 + Diabetes, family = binomial, data = selected.table)
